    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-28T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-28T05:00:00-05:00" n="161"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d161">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/9871</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-28T11:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 28, 1918, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 23, 10.46 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1310. War Trade Board [from <persName>Frothingham</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 1298. <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_FPj1">Fuller</persName>. Refer
                    our 1259, August 19. Conference plan for enemy trade licensing seems likely [to
                    fail on] account the lack of interest here. In order to press matter here would
                    appreciate your advices as to what we stand to gain by conference control in
                    contrast to previous informal procedure of exchanging copies of licenses granted
                    by London and Washington to their respective nationals.
                        <persName>Frothingham</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
